Lecture 7 | Representation

Plan for Today

  • Discuss constituencies

Who are Constituents?

  • Fenno (1977, 1978) details the different constituencies that members are responsive to

    • Geographic Constituency

      • All potential voters in a region

    • Electoral Supporters

      • Those who will vote for the member in elections

    • Primary Supporters

      • Those who will work for the member (go the extra mile!)

    • Candidate’s Inner Circle

      • Family, close friends, and advisers

The Ever Changing Geographic Constituency

  • Generally, we think of the geographic constituency as the boundary that contains all people within a geographic area

  • Elected officials tend to think of this geographic constituency as the area that contains not the total population, but rather the number of eligible voters

    • Basis of electoral accountability

  • Therefore, geographic constituencies have changed dramatically over time

    • Initially, only white, mainly protestant, property owners could vote

      • We continue to see this division between the social elites and common person

    • Then none land owners, but gainfully employed white men could vote

    • Then voting rights are established in the Constitution with the 15th Amendment

      • Can’t deny anyone the right to vote based on the color of their skin

      • Unfortunately, the 15th Amendment only stipulates the conditions in which the right to vote cannot be denied, it does not cover other reasons that the right to vote could be denied

  • Women are granted the right to vote in 1920

    • 19th Amendment

  • The geographic constituency continues to change, especially in the South, during the Jim Crow Era

    • Poll tax, literacy tests, and other exclusionary practices

      • These restrictions are not based on race. Therefore, many white voters were disenfranchised

        • Grandfather Clauses

          • If your grandfather had the right to vote, then you did too

      • These restrictions are abolished with the 24th Amendment (1964) and the Voting Rights Act of 1965

  • Lastly, the number of eligible voters was changed based on age

    • 26th Amendment (1971)

National Representation

  • Thinking outside of the concentric circles

  • Members utilize their committee assignments and policy agendas to pursue national interests

    • Senators are more likely to have national constituencies

      • Fewer of them, more impact on policy, powerful committee assignments

  • Policy focus

  • Political ambition

    • Want to run for national offices (i.e., president)

Substantive Representation

  • Substance equals policy content

  • Policy congruence

    • How well do a legislator’s issue or policy positions correspond to what their constituents want

  • Voters can keep up with votes (public information)

Descriptive Representation

  • Do legislators “look” like their constituents?

  • Many scholars argue that better descriptive representation leads to better substantive representation

  • For example: do African American representatives provide better representation of African American interests

    • Research suggests, based on roll call voting, that this seems to be the case

      • Research on the Latino population is less developed, but the current research finds similar results

Collective Representation

  • The connection between Congress as a whole and the American public

  • Does Congress reflect the wishes of the American public?

Final Thoughts

  • Elected officials focus on those people that are eligible voters

  • The public disapproves of Congress as a whole, but largely approves of their own members
